It suggests that the interwoven discourses sparked by these commodities transformed the period’s literary Orientalism and created surprisingly self-reflexive ways through which British writers encountered and imagined cultural otherness. Tracing exotic ingestion as a motif across a range of authors and genres, this book considers how, why, and whither writers used scenes of eating, drinking, and smoking to diagnose and interrogate their own solipsistic constructions of the Orient. As national and cultural boundaries became increasingly porous, such self-reflexive inquiries into the nature and role of otherness provided an unexpected avenue for British imperial subjectivity to emerge and coalesce.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aConsumption (Economics)xSocial aspectszGreat BritainxHistory. 0aLuxury goods industryzGreat BritainxHistory. 0aOrientalismzGreat BritainxHistory. 0aOther (Philosophy). 70(DE-588)4014777-00(DE-627)1063387490(DE-576)208909400aEnglisch2gnd 70(DE-588)4035964-50(DE-627)1062450150(DE-576)209015608aLiteratur2gnd 70(DE-588)4138928-10(DE-627)1056390280(DE-576)209690135aDer Andere2gnd 70(DE-588)4153341-00(DE-627)1055316420(DE-576)209802588aExotik2gnd 70(DE-588)4232369-10(DE-627)1049254770(DE-576)210363274aNahrunggMotiv2gnd 70(DE-588)4516666-30(DE-627)2493539620(DE-576)213244209aGenussmittelgMotiv2gnd 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aThe Citizen of the World, Oliver Goldsmith, Vathek, William Beckford, Lalla Rookh, Thomas Moore, The Talisman, Walter Scott, Confessions of an English Opium-Eater, Thomas De Quincy, Charles Lamb, Opium Wars, Villette, Charlotte Brontë, Little Dorrit, Charles Dickens, Consumption, Consumerism, Exotic goods, Exotic consumerism, Exotic ingestion, Commodities, Tea discourse, Imperial identity, Cultural identity, Empir